[{"id":"VR803596","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR803594.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">After each trial, the permanent magnet is removed from the room where the experiment is done. With the permanent bar magnet now removed, the sensor would detect the presence of a magnetic field generated by which, if either, of the two metallic bars in trials <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> ?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR803596_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<html><body><div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figures 1, 2, and 3 each show a stationary bar magnet with a magnetic field sensor near its north pole. In each figure, the bar magnet is oriented horizontally with its north pole to the right. Figure 1 shows nothing to the right of the magnetic field sensor. Figure 2 shows an iron bar aligned with the bar magnet and positioned to the right of the magnetic field sensor. Figure 3 shows an aluminum bar aligned with the bar magnet and positioned to the right of the magnetic field sensor.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR803594.g01.svg\"/></div><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><p class=\"passage_para\">A student conducts an experiment using a sensitive magnetic field sensor. Three measurements are made with the sensor at the same fixed distance from the north pole of a stationary permanent bar magnet. In Trial <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> only the permanent magnet is near the sensor, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. In Trial <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> an initially unmagnetized iron bar is aligned with the bar magnet and positioned at an equal distance on the opposite side of the sensor, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. In Trial <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> an aluminum bar is aligned with the bar magnet and positioned at an equal distance on the opposite side of the sensor, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>. The iron and aluminum bars have the same dimensions.</p></div></div></div></body></html>"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Neither the iron nor the aluminum bar</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Only the aluminum bar</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Only the iron bar</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both the iron and the aluminum bar</p>"],"answer":2}]